 \u003cem\u003epraviśanti\u003c/em\u003e – enter into; \u003cem\u003eye\u003c/em\u003e – those who; \u003cem\u003easambhūtim\u003c/em\u003e – demigods; \u003cem\u003eupāsate\u003c/em\u003e – worship; \u003cem\u003etataḥ\u003c/em\u003e – than that; \u003cem\u003ebhūyaḥ\u003c/em\u003e – still more; \u003cem\u003eiva\u003c/em\u003e – like that; \u003cem\u003ete\u003c/em\u003e – those; \u003cem\u003etamaḥ\u003c/em\u003e – darkness; \u003cem\u003eye\u003c/em\u003e – who; \u003cem\u003eu\u003c/em\u003e – also; \u003cem\u003esambhūtyām\u003c/em\u003e – in the Absolute; \u003cem\u003eratāḥ\u003c/em\u003e – engaged.\",\"word_for_word_value\":[{\"word\":\"andham\",\"translation\":\"ignorance\"},{\"word\":\"tamaḥ\",\"translation\":\"darkness\"},{\"word\":\"praviśanti\",\"translation\":\"enter into\"},{\"word\":\"ye\",\"translation\":\"those who\"},{\"word\":\"asambhūtim\",\"translation\":\"demigods\"},{\"word\":\"upāsate\",\"translation\":\"worship\"},{\"word\":\"tataḥ\",\"translation\":\"than that\"},{\"word\":\"bhūyaḥ\",\"translation\":\"still more\"},{\"word\":\"iva\",\"translation\":\"like that\"},{\"word\":\"te\",\"translation\":\"those\"},{\"word\":\"tamaḥ\",\"translation\":\"darkness\"},{\"word\":\"ye\",\"translation\":\"who\"},{\"word\":\"u\",\"translation\":\"also\"},{\"word\":\"sambhūtyām\",\"translation\":\"in the Absolute\"},{\"word\":\"ratāḥ\",\"translation\":\"engaged\"}]}]},{\"section\":\"translation\",\"section_title\":\"Books.Verse.translation\",\"children\":[{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"translation\",\"id\":94104,\"bb\":93631,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93631/\",\"body_value\":\"Those who are engaged in the worship of demigods enter into the darkest region of ignorance, and still more so do the worshipers of the impersonal Absolute.\"}]},{\"section\":\"purport\",\"section_title\":\"Books.Verse.purport\",\"children\":[{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94105,\"bb\":93632,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93632/\",\"body_value\":\"The Sanskrit word \u003cem\u003easambhūti\u003c/em\u003e refers to those who have no independent existence. \u003cem\u003eSambhūti\u003c/em\u003e is the Absolute Personality of Godhead, who is absolutely independent of everything. In the \u003ca href=\\\"/en/library/bg/10/2/\\\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eBhagavad-gītā\u003c/em\u003e (10.2)\u003c/a\u003e, the Absolute Personality of Godhead, Śrī Kṛṣṇa, states:\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"verse_text\",\"id\":94106,\"bb\":93633,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93633/\",\"body_value\":\"\u003cem\u003ena me viduḥ sura-gaṇāḥ\u003cbr /\u003eprabhavaṁ na maharṣayaḥ\u003cbr /\u003eaham ādir hi devānāṁ\u003cbr /\u003emaharṣīṇāṁ ca sarvaśaḥ\u003c/em\u003e\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94107,\"bb\":93634,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93634/\",\"body_value\":\"“Neither the hosts of demigods nor the great sages know My origin or opulences, for in every respect I am the source of the demigods and sages.” Thus Kṛṣṇa is the origin of the powers delegated to demigods, great sages and mystics. Although they are endowed with great powers, these powers are limited, and thus it is very difficult for them to know how Kṛṣṇa Himself appears by His own internal potency in the form of a man.\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94108,\"bb\":93635,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93635/\",\"body_value\":\"Many philosophers and great \u003cem\u003eṛṣis,\u003c/em\u003e or mystics, try to distinguish the Absolute from the relative by their tiny brain power. This can only help them reach the negative conception of the Absolute without realizing any positive trace of the Absolute. Definition of the Absolute by negation is not complete. Such negative definitions lead one to create a concept of one’s own; thus one imagines that the Absolute must be formless and without qualities. Such negative qualities are simply the reversals of relative, material qualities and are therefore also relative. By conceiving of the Absolute in this way, one can at the utmost reach the impersonal effulgence of God, known as Brahman, but one cannot make further progress to Bhagavān, the Personality of Godhead.\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94109,\"bb\":93636,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93636/\",\"body_value\":\"Such mental speculators do not know that the Absolute Personality of Godhead is Kṛṣṇa, that the impersonal Brahman is the glaring effulgence of His transcendental body, or that the Paramātmā, the Supersoul, is His all-pervading plenary representation. Nor do they know that Kṛṣṇa has His eternal form with its transcendental qualities of eternal bliss and knowledge. The dependent demigods and great sages imperfectly consider Him to be a powerful demigod, and they consider the Brahman effulgence to be the Absolute Truth. But the devotees of Kṛṣṇa, by dint of their surrendering unto Him and their unalloyed devotion, can know that He is the Absolute Person and that everything emanates from Him. Such devotees continuously render loving service unto Kṛṣṇa, the fountainhead of everything.\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94110,\"bb\":93637,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93637/\",\"body_value\":\"In the \u003cem\u003eBhagavad-gītā\u003c/em\u003e (7.20, 23) it is said that only unintelligent, bewildered persons driven by a strong desire for sense gratification worship the demigods for the temporary relief of temporary problems. Since the living being is materially entangled, he has to be relieved from material bondage entirely to attain permanent relief on the spiritual plane, where eternal bliss, life and knowledge exist. \u003cem\u003eŚrī Īśopaniṣad\u003c/em\u003e therefore instructs that we should not seek temporary relief of our difficulties by worshiping the dependent demigods, who can bestow only temporary benefit. Rather, we must worship the Absolute Personality of Godhead, Kṛṣṇa, who is all-attractive and who can bestow upon us complete freedom from material bondage by taking us back home, back to Godhead.\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94111,\"bb\":93638,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93638/\",\"body_value\":\"$4d\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"verse_text\",\"id\":94112,\"bb\":93639,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93639/\",\"body_value\":\"\u003cem\u003eā-brahma-bhuvanāl lokāḥ\u003cbr /\u003epunar āvartino ’rjuna\u003cbr /\u003emām upetya tu kaunteya\u003cbr /\u003epunar janma na vidyate\u003c/em\u003e\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94113,\"bb\":93640,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93640/\",\"body_value\":\"“From the highest planet in the material world down to the lowest, all are places of misery wherein repeated birth and death take place. But one who attains My abode, O son of Kuntī, never takes birth again.”\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94114,\"bb\":93641,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93641/\",\"body_value\":\"$4e\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94115,\"bb\":93642,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93642/\",\"body_value\":\"$4f\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94116,\"bb\":93643,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93643/\",\"body_value\":\"$50\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94117,\"bb\":93644,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93644/\",\"body_value\":\"$51\"},{\"type\":\"content.Record\",\"title\":\"paragraph\",\"id\":94118,\"bb\":93645,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/12/b93645/\",\"body_value\":\"These rogues are the most dangerous elements in human society. Because there is no religious government, they escape punishment by the law of the state. They cannot, however, escape the law of the Supreme, who has clearly declared in the \u003cem\u003eBhagavad-gītā\u003c/em\u003e that envious demons in the garb of religious propagandists shall be thrown into the darkest regions of hell (\u003cem\u003eBhagavad-gītā\u003c/em\u003e 16.19–20). \u003cem\u003eŚrī Īśopaniṣad\u003c/em\u003e confirms that these pseudo religionists are heading toward the most obnoxious place in the universe after the completion of their spiritual master business, which they conduct simply for sense gratification.\"}]}],\"short_title\":\"Iso 12\",\"medium_title\":\"Śrī Īśopaniṣad 12\"},{\"id\":94119,\"meta\":{\"type\":\"books.Verse\",\"slug\":\"13\",\"show_in_menus\":false,\"seo_title\":\"\",\"search_description\":\"\",\"first_published_at\":null,\"alias_of\":null,\"locale\":\"en\"},\"title\":\"Mantra Thirteen\",\"advanced_view_url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/advanced-view/#bb93646\",\"language_menu\":[{\"display_name\":\"አማርኛ (Ethiopian)\",\"language_code\":\"am\",\"enabled\":true,\"url_path\":\"/am/library/iso/13/\"},{\"display_name\":\"Български (Bulgarian)\",\"language_code\":\"bg\",\"enabled\":true,\"url_path\":\"/bg/library/iso/13/\"},{\"display_name\":\"Čeština (Czech)\",\"language_code\":\"cs\",\"enabled\":true,\"url_path\":\"/cs/library/iso/13/\"},{\"display_name\":\"Dansk (Danish)\",\"language_code\":\"da\",\"enabled\":false,\"url_path\":\"/da/\"},{\"display_name\":\"Deutsch (German)\",\"language_code\":\"de\",\"enabled\":true,\"url_path\":\"/de/library/iso/13/\"},{\"display_name\":\"English\",\"language_code\":\"en\",\"enabled\":true,\"url_path\":\"/en/library/iso/13/\"},{\"display_name\":\"Español (Spanish)\",\"language_code\":\"es\",\"enabled\":true,\"url_path\":\"/es/library/iso/13/\"},{\"display_name\":\"Eesti keel (Estonian)\",\"language_code\":\"et\",\"enabled\":true,\"url_path\":\"/et/library/iso/13/\"},{\"display_name\":\"Suomen kieli (Finnish)\",\"language_code\":\"fi\",\"enabled\":false,\"url_path\":\"/fi/\"},{\"display_name\":\"Français (French)\",\"language_code\":\"fr\",\"enabled\":true,\"url_path\":\"/fr/library/iso/13/\"},{\"display_name\":\"Hrvatski (Croatian)\",\"language_code\